metadata.name: Returns #228
metadata.description:
Returns is an offline-first PWA and an interactive SVG. It combines the joy of interaction, digital color and minimalist sculpture with the potential of a long running, continuously unique visual. Based on “Shipping” from 2016, it is inspired by Anne Truitt, Ugo Rondinone, Imi Knoebel, Kelly Ellsworth and many others.

A subdivision slices the viewport influenced by width, height and depth. Corners are cut by replacing them with two new points, pulled towards each other along the edges. Shapes are “rounded" by repeating this step, keeping the new points close together. As colors change, so do the relations between shapes, even if geometry changes at a slower pace. New compositions are created on click or after a timeout. This progress over time allows for infinite iterations within the space of each token. It is the promise of a seeded starting point, plus the potential for unlimited new and unique iterations and states over time.

metadata.name: Shattered Moons #247
metadata.description:
🌘🌗🌖Shattered Moons🌔🌓🌒

Explore deep space moons through this pure SVG generative experiment.

Features:
- Striped Background
- Shadows
- Vapors
- Horizontal Vapors
- Meteors
- Colored Meteors
- White Moon (0.5%)

SVG being a vectorial format, this work can be displayed/printed at any size.
Press 's' on Live View to save the SVG.
Press 'p' on Live View using a Chromium based browser to export as PNG.

Also, to fully enjoy your piece, I'd suggest to use a Chromium based browser as the SVG renderer gives more details.

metadata.name: Cables and Clouds #159
metadata.description:
Capturing clouds... an old dream of mad scientist... coming true...
But wait... are they real clouds ? Maybe... maybe not...
Is it the real life ?
Is this just fantasy ?

Interaction.
Press h in live mode to list the possibilities.
Key 's'  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution
Key 'c' to change color palette
Key 'd' to toggle a special color mode to highlight the different components (and have the number of points used in your specific drawing).

Features.
18 different features displayed (format, color palettes, main elements characteristics, rare elements...).

metadata.name: Décollage #52
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of décollage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).

metadata.name: GRAPHEME #250
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. 
www.tribute-hwf.com

“One criterion for art involves the process used by the artist for shaping the work. In the special case of mathematically supported fine art, the artmaking process occurs in a mathematically defined operation that allows the generation and transformation of images, methods used for picture processing.” - Herbert W. Franke

I first came across Franke’s ‘Ornamental Alphabets’ in his book 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘎𝘳𝘢𝘱𝘩𝘪𝘤𝘴 - 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘈𝘳𝘵, and was intrigued with the idea of using a simple letterform to explore different generative image processing techniques. 

I’ve used letters and writing in my work for a long time, both with letterpress printing and in my asemic poetry programs. With asemic writing, I generate unrecognizable letters to reference text, and here I use recognizable letterforms removed from their typical function as language signifiers. 

My goal with this project was to build as much texture and layering as possible by warping and collaging the letters together in various ways. The font I’m using is a design I made years ago to supplement my wood type collection for printing. I really enjoyed being able to bring that part of my past work into my generative art practice. 

Each image is composed of the letters found in the hash for that piece, divided into either vowels or consonants. The program builds on a technique I’ve used before, where I generate an image to an off-screen canvas and then dive through the pixels to pull out the color and form I want to surface in the final image.

25% of the primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. These funds will be used by ZKM Karlsruhe to digitize Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any additional funds raised will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

- Press “R” to increase the pixel density and reload the image (this can be render intensive and will create a really large file suitable for printing)
- Press “S” to save a copy

Made with p5js
Artist: Sarah Ridgley
October, 2022

metadata.name: Breakdown #324
metadata.description:
The key to solving a difficult problem is to break it down into a series of smaller, more tractable, problems.

Here we start with a rectangular polygon. We shrink our polygon by some fixed amount (inset), and then pick a point inside it. We then send off rays in N evenly spaced directions and use these to split the polygon into N new polygons. Repeat the process, varying parameters such as how we pick our point or the angles of our projected rays, and see what emerges.

Press 'v' to download an svg output.

metadata.name: Ornamental Tree #38
metadata.description:
A simple tree in a grassy field. Released as a thank you gift to holders of Orchard, Grove, and Deep Forest.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 3000x3000px

Common Features:
- One of three seasons: spring, summer, or fall
- 50/50 square or circle shaped trees
- Percent distance haze
- Neutral or blue sky color
- 50/50 color or background tinted clouds
- Color tints for highlights and shadows
- If spring or summer, 50/50 chance of flowers
- Smooth rolling hills or not

metadata.name: Grove #178
metadata.description:
A generative, impressionist painting of a small grove of trees in one of the four seasons. In spring and summer, flowers bloom in the meadow. A rare variation will create a charcoal drawing on white or black paper. Super rare will create a lighted winter scene that may have a moon behind the tree.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press 's' to save a screenshot at any point. Image size is 1400x1082px.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 3,000 px.

On the paintings only, adding '&bg=true' will stop the painting after the background. Adding '&size=3000&bg=true' will give you a nice desktop background! 

Common Features:
- About 12-14 trees
- One of the four seasons
- One of 12 highlight color tints
- One of 12 shadow color tints
- Varying levels of distance haze
- Varying max brush sizes
- Varying amount of colors in the strokes

Less Common
- 15% chance of a charcoal drawing
- 50% chance it to be a dark winter scene

Rare
- Winter drawing with lights on the tree

Super Rare
- Winter drawing with a moon behind the tree

Copyright (c) 2022 Matt Perkins, hello@mattperkins.me, @nudoru on Twitter. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Cold Mountain #341
metadata.description:
An impressionistic painting of a maintain on a foggy winter's day. The view will be of a mountain, mountain range, valley, or meadow. At nite, the lights come on, and the trees glow in the moonlight.

The image size is 928x1200. Press 's' to save a screenshot.

Common features:
- mountain size and stroke quality
- line quality of the trees
- 50/50 to have a spiral around the sun
- large palette with different application methods

Uncommon
- outline of the first mountain and sun
- amplified color/hue shifting

Rare
- nighttime
- no sun
